    </introduction>

    <exercise>
      <title>Reynolds number estimation</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          <em>Based on Problem 2.1 in <xref ref="ref-acheson"/>.</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          Give an order-of-magnitude estimate of the Reynolds number in each of the following situations:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            flow past the wing of a jumbo jet at 150 m/s (roughly half the speed of sound);
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The kinematic viscosity of air at standard temperature and pressure is
            about <m>1.5\times10^{-5}~\textrm{m}^2/\textrm{s}</m>.
            The wingspan of a jumbo jet is about <m>60~\textrm{m}</m>, so the Reynolds
            number is approximately
            <me>
              \textrm{Re}=\frac{UL}{\nu}
              =\frac{150\times60}{1.5\times10^{-5}}
              =6\times10^8.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            blood flow in a large artery (diameter 2 cm) at 0.3 m/s;
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The kinematic viscosity of blood is about <m>2.4\times10^{-6}~\textrm{m}^2/\textrm{s}</m>.
            The diameter of the artery is about <m>0.02~\textrm{m}</m>, so the Reynolds
            number is approximately
            <me>
              \textrm{Re}=\frac{UL}{\nu}
              =\frac{0.3\times0.02}{2.4\times10^{-6}}
              =2500.
            </me>
            Although this is above 2000, blood flow in arteries is typically laminar.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            a thick layer of honey draining off a spoon at 1 cm/s;
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The kinematic viscosity of honey is about <m>0.007~\textrm{m}^2/\textrm{s}</m>.
            The thickness of the layer is about <m>0.005~\textrm{m}</m>, so the Reynolds
            number is approximately
            <me>
              \textrm{Re}=\frac{UL}{\nu}
              =\frac{0.01\times0.005}{0.007}
              \approx0.007.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            a spermatozoon with tail length <m>10^{-3}</m> swimming at 100 <m>\mu</m>m/s in water.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The kinematic viscosity of water at room temperature is about
            <m>10^{-6}~\textrm{m}^2/\textrm{s}</m>. The length of the tail is about
            <m>10^{-3}~\textrm{m}</m>, so the Reynolds number is approximately
            <me>
              \textrm{Re}=\frac{UL}{\nu}
              =\frac{100\times10^{-6}\times10^{-3}}{10^{-6}}
              =0.1.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Nondimensionalisation</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          <em>Based on Problem 2.2 in <xref ref="ref-acheson"/></em>
        </p>
        <p>
          In this problem you will work through the nondimensionalisation of
          a typical fluid flow problem to identify the Reynolds number as a key
          dimensionless parameter.
        </p>
        <p>
          Consider the two-dimensional steady flow of a viscous incompressible fluid
          past a circular cylinder of radius <m>a</m>.
          Far from the cylinder, the fluid velocity is uniform with magnitude <m>U</m>
          in the <m>x</m>-direction.
          The governing equations are the incompressible Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations
          and continuity equation:
          <me>
            \left(\bu\cdot\nabla\right)\bu=-\frac{1}{\rho}\nabla p+\nu\nabla^2\bu,\quad
            \nabla\cdot\bu=0,
          </me>
          where <m>\bu=(u,v)</m> is the velocity field, <m>p</m> is the pressure field,
          <m>\rho</m> is the fluid density,
          and <m>\nu</m> is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write down suitable boundary conditions at the cylinder surface
            and far from the cylinder.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            At the cylinder surface, we have the no-slip and no-penetration
            boundary conditions:
            <me>
              u=v=0.
            </me>
            Far from the cylinder, the velocity approaches the uniform flow:
            <me>
              u\rightarrow U,\quad v\rightarrow0\quad\textrm{as }\sqrt{x^2+y^2}\rightarrow\infty.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Introduce nondimensional variables
            <me>
              x^*=\frac{x}{a},\quad y^*=\frac{y}{a},\quad
              u^*=\frac{u}{U},\quad v^*=\frac{v}{U},\quad
              p^*=\frac{p}{\rho U^2}.
            </me>
            Rewrite the governing equations and boundary conditions in terms of
            these nondimensional variables.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We have:
            <me>
              \frac{U^2}{L}\left(\bu^*\cdot\nabla^*\right)\bu^*
              =-\frac{U^2}{L}\nabla^*p^*
              +\frac{\nu U}{L^2}\nabla^{*2}\bu^*,\quad
              \frac{U}{L}\nabla^*\cdot\bu^*=0,
            </me>
            which simplify to
            <me>
              \mathrm{Re}\left(\bu^*\cdot\nabla^*\right)\bu^*
              =-\mathrm{Re}\nabla^*p^*
              +\nabla^{*2}\bu^*,\quad
              \nabla^*\cdot\bu^*=0,
            </me>
            while the boundary conditions become:
            <me>
              u^*=v^*=0
            </me>
            at <m>x^{*2}+y^{*2}=1</m> and
            <me>
              u^*\rightarrow 1,\quad v^*\rightarrow0\quad\textrm{as }\sqrt{x^{*2}+y^{*2}}\rightarrow\infty.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            You should have found that the nondimensional problem depends
            only on a single parameter: the Reynolds number.
            Thus flows at equal Reynolds numbers are geometrically similar,
            and one only needs to know the Reynolds number to understand the
            flow.
          </p>
          <p>
            This was a particularly simple problem
            that has an unambiguous length and velocity scale,
            and so nondimensionalisation of the problem works particularly well.
            However, it is frequently helpful to nondimensionalise problems before
            solving so that key dimensionless groups of parameters
            (such as the Reynolds number) can be identified.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ps-falling-ball-viscometer">
      <title>Falling ball viscometer</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For slowly moving spheres, the resistive force is given by Stokes
          drag, and equals <m>3\pi\mu Du</m>, where <m>D</m> is the diameter of the sphere, <m>\mu</m>
          is the dynamic viscosity of the fluid, and <m>u</m> is the speed of the sphere
          (this is a famous result).
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Check the dimensions of the Stokes drag. Is the dimension what you expect?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The dimensions of the terms are as follows:
            <me>
              [3\pi]=1,\quad
              [\mu]=ML^{-1}T^{-1},\quad
              [D]=L,\quad
              [u]=LT^{-1},
            </me>
            meaning that
            <me>
              \left[3\pi\mu Du\right]=1\times ML^{-1}T^{-1}\times L\times LT^{-1}
              =MLT^{-2}.
            </me>
            Thus the expression <m>3\pi\mu Du</m> for the Stokes drag
            has the dimensions of force, as expected.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A steel ballbearing of mass <m>m</m>, diameter <m>D</m> falls slowly through a
            viscous fluid of dynamic viscosity <m>\mu</m>. In this question you can neglect
            the buoyancy force. What are the other two forces acting on the ballbearing?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Gravity and fluid drag
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write down a differential equation for the time-evolution of the velocity
            <m>u</m> of the ballbearing, assuming that the acceleration due to gravity
            is <m>g</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Newton's second law gives
            <me>
              m\frac{du}{dt}=mg-3\pi\mu Du.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given that the ballbearing is released from rest, solve the differential
            equation to show that
            <me>
              u=u_t\left(1-e^{-t/\tau}\right),
            </me>
            where <m>u_t</m> and <m>\tau</m> are constant parameters that you should define.
            What is the physical significance of <m>u_t</m> and <m>\tau</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We have
            <me>
              \frac{du}{dt}+\frac{3\pi\mu D}{m}u=g,
            </me>
            for which the integrating factor is <m>e^{\frac{3\pi\mu D}{m}t}</m>, and
            <me>
              ue^{\frac{3\pi\mu D}{m}t}=\int ge^{\frac{3\pi\mu D}{m}t}dt
              =\frac{mg}{3\pi\mu D}e^{\frac{3\pi\mu D}{m}t}+c,
            </me>
            where <m>c</m> is a constant of integration. Hence
            <me>
              u=\frac{mg}{3\pi\mu D}+ce^{-\frac{3\pi\mu D}{m}t}
            </me>
            The initial condition is <m>u=0</m> at <m>t=0</m>, and,
            substituting this into the above equation,
            <m>0=\frac{mg}{3\pi\mu D}+c</m>, giving <m>c=-\frac{mg}{3\pi\mu D}</m>. Hence
            <me>
              u=\frac{mg}{3\pi\mu D}\left(1-e^{-\frac{3\pi\mu D}{m}t}\right).
            </me>
            We substitute <m>u_t=\frac{mg}{3\pi\mu D}</m> and <m>\tau=\frac{m}{3\pi\mu D}</m>.
            With these substitutions we get
            <me>
              u=u_t\left(1-e^{-t/\tau}\right).
            </me>
            The physical significance of these choices is that <m>u_t</m>
            is the terminal velocity of the sphere and <m>\tau</m> is the timescale over
            which the velocity of the sphere approaches the terminal velocity.
            Every <m>\tau</m> units of time, the velocity of the sphere becomes closer
            to the terminal velocity <m>u_t</m> by a factor <m>e\approx2.7</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Sketch the velocity as a function of time.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <figure xml:id="ball-low-re">
            <caption>Sketch of velocity as a function of time.</caption>
            <image source="ch-chapter07-ball-low-re.png" width="80%"/>
          </figure>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the ballbearing has diameter 2 mm and is falling through glycerol at
            20<m>^\circ</m>C, what is its terminal velocity in mm/s and what is the
            timescale taken to reach the terminal velocity? You may assume that the
            dynamic viscosity of glycerol at 20<m>^\circ</m>C is 1.2 Pa s and the density
            of steel is 8,000 kg/m<m>^3</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Using the fact that the volume of a sphere is
            <m>\pi D^3/6</m>, where <m>D</m> is the diameter,
            we have <m>m=\pi\rho_sD^3/6</m>, where <m>\rho_s=8,000</m> kg/m<m>^3</m>. Thus
            <md>
              <mrow>u_t=&amp;\frac{mg}{3\pi\mu D}=\frac{mg}{3\pi\mu D}=\frac{\rho_sgD^2}{18\mu}</mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac{8000\times9.81\times(4\times10^{-6})}{18\times1.2}
                =0.0146\,\textrm{m/s}=14.6\,\textrm{mm/s}.
              </mrow>
            </md>
            The timescale <m>\tau</m> is given by
            <me>
              \tau=\frac{m}{3\pi\mu D}=\frac{\rho_sD^2}{18\mu}
              =\frac{8000\times4\times10^{-6}}{18\times1.2}
              =0.00148\,\textrm{s}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Comment on the experimental set up needed to measure the terminal velocity.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The ball would attain its terminal velocity very quickly (in much less than a second),
            and since <m>u_t</m> is on order of centimetres per second, a container of about 10 cm
            deep would be suitable for measurement. In fact this idea is commonly used to measure
            the viscosity of fluids (since the viscosity can be calculated from the terminal velocity);
            this is called a <em>falling ball viscometer</em>.              
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ps-stress-plate">
      <title>Stress on a plate</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          A rigid plate of length <m>L</m> is fixed along the line <m>y=kx</m> and has width
          <m>W</m> in the <m>z</m>-direction.
          An incompressible fluid of density <m>\rho</m> and viscosity <m>\mu</m> flows steadily
          in the shaded region <m>y>kx</m>, shown in <xref ref="plate-sketch"/>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="plate-sketch">
          <caption>Sketch of plate.</caption>
          <image source="ch-chapter07-plate.jpg" width="50%" />
        </figure>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given that the velocity field is
            <me>
              u=\alpha y+Ax+B,\quad v=-Ay+Dx+C,
            </me>
            what are <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, <m>D</m>
            in terms of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>k</m>?
            Simplify the velocity components <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>.
            (Note that the fact that the coefficients on the terms
            <m>Ax</m> in <m>u</m> and <m>-Ay</m> in <m>v</m> are equal and opposite
            is required to ensure incompressibility of the fluid).
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We apply no-slip boundary conditions at the plate.
            Thus if <m>y=kx</m> then we must have <m>u=0</m> and <m>v=0</m>. Hence
            <me>
              0=\alpha kx+Ax+B,\quad 0=-Akx+Dx+C,
            </me>
            for all <m>x</m>, which implies that <m>\alpha k+A=0</m>, <m>B=0</m>,
            <m>-Ak+D=0</m> and <m>C=0</m>. Solving, we obtain
            <me>
              A=-\alpha k,\quad
              B=0,\quad
              D=-\alpha k^2,\quad
              C=0.  
            </me>
            Hence
            <me>
              u=\alpha\left(y-kx\right),\quad v=\alpha k\left(y-kx\right).
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the drag force on the plate.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            The drag force can be found by changing coordinates from
            <m>(x,y)</m> to <m>(\xi,\eta)</m>,
            which are Cartesian coordinates where the <m>\xi</m>-axis runs along the plate
            and the <m>\eta</m>-axis goes from the plate perpendicularly into the fluid.
            You may use the fact that
            <me>
              \boldsymbol{i}=\cos\theta\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}-\sin\theta\hat{\boldsymbol{\eta}},\qquad
              \boldsymbol{j}=\sin\theta\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}+\cos\theta\hat{\boldsymbol{\eta}},
            </me>
            where <m>\boldsymbol{i}</m>, <m>\boldsymbol{j}</m> are unit vectors in the <m>x</m>-
            and <m>y</m>-directions, respectively, and <m>\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}</m>, <m>\hat{\boldsymbol{\eta}}</m>
            are unit vectors in the <m>\xi</m>- and <m>\eta</m>-directions, respectively, and <m>\theta</m>
            is the angle between the plate and the <m>x</m>-axis.
            You may use the fact that <m>\cos\theta=1/(\sqrt{1+k^2})</m>,
            <m>\sin\theta=k/(\sqrt{1+k^2})</m> and
            <me>
              x=\frac{\xi}{\sqrt{1+k^2}}-\frac{k\eta}{\sqrt{1+k^2}},\quad
              y=\frac{k\xi}{\sqrt{1+k^2}}+\frac{\eta}{\sqrt{1+k^2}}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </hint>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We perform the coordinate transform illustrated in <xref ref="plate-coordinates"/>
            from the <m>(x,y)</m>-plane to the <m>(\xi,\eta)</m>-plane:
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="plate-coordinates">
            <caption>Sketch of plate.</caption>
            <image source="ch-chapter07-plate-coordinates.jpg" width="100%" />
          </figure>
          <p>
            We use
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \bu=&amp;u\boldsymbol{i}+v\boldsymbol{j}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;u\left(\cos\theta\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}-\sin\theta\hat{\boldsymbol{\eta}}\right)
                +v\left(\sin\theta\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}+\cos\theta\hat{\boldsymbol{\eta}}\right)
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\left(u\cos\theta+v\sin\theta\right)\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
                +\left(-u\sin\theta+v\cos\theta\right)\hat{\boldsymbol{\eta}}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac{\alpha(y-kx)+\alpha k^2(y-kx)}{\sqrt{1+k^2}}\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
                +\frac{-\alpha k(y-kx)+\alpha k(y-kx)}{\sqrt{1+k^2}}\hat{\boldsymbol{\eta}}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\alpha\sqrt{1+k^2}(y-kx)\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\alpha\sqrt{1+k^2}\sqrt{1+k^2}\eta\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\alpha(1+k^2)\eta\hat{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
              </mrow>
            </md>
            and so the velocity components are <m>u_\xi=\alpha(1+k^2)\eta</m> and <m>u_\eta=0</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Thus the shear stress is given by
            <me>
              \mu\pd{u_\xi}{\eta}=\mu\alpha(1+k^2),
            </me>
            and hence the drag force equals
            <me>
              \mu\alpha(1+k^2)LW.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ps-stress-pressure">
      <title>Stress on a surface due to the pressure</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          In this problem, you will calculate the resultant force on the cube shown in
          <xref ref="fig-small-cube"/> due to the pressure in the surrounding fluid acting on the fluid
          within the cube.
          We will consider two different methods of calculating this force.
        </p>
        <p>
          Note that, in this question, as with the derivation of the
          Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations <xref ref="eqn-navierstokes"/>,
          you may use some sleight of hand, so as to avoid carefully integrating
          the force over the surface.
          However, as in that case, fortunately the errors cancel and the result is correct.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Assuming that the pressure <m>p(x,y,z)</m> is uniform over the surface
            <m>x=x_0</m> and over the surface <m>x=x_0+\delta</m>,
            calculate the force on the fluid in the cube due to the pressure of the
            surrounding fluid on these two faces and show that it is approximately
            <me>-\delta^3\pd{p}{x}\bi=-V\pd{p}{x}\bi,</me>
            where <m>V=\delta^3</m> is the volume of the cube.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The force on <m>x=x_0</m> is pressure times area acting into the cube,
            which is <m>\delta^2p|_{x_0}\bi</m>, while the force on <m>x=x_0+\delta</m>
            equals <m>-\delta^2p|_{x+\delta}\bi</m>.
            Hence the contribution to the force from these two faces is
            <me>\delta^2p|_{x_0}\bi-\delta^2p|_{x+\delta}\bi
              \approx-\delta^3\pd{p}{x}\bi=-V\pd{p}{x}\bi.</me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Similarly, calculate the force on the fluid in the cube due to the pressure of the
            surrounding fluid on the faces <m>y=y_0</m> and <m>y=y_0+\delta</m>,
            and on the faces <m>z=z_0</m> and <m>z=z_0+\delta</m>.
            Hence show that the total force on the fluid in the cube due to the pressure
            of the surrounding fluid is given by
            <me>-V\pd{p}{x}\bi-V\pd{p}{y}\bj-V\pd{p}{z}\bk=-V\nabla p.</me>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The force on <m>y=y_0</m> is <m>\delta^2p|_{y_0}\bj</m> and that on <m>y=y_0+\delta</m>
            is <m>-\delta^2p|_{y+\delta}\bj</m>. This gives a contribution
            <me>\delta^2p|_{y_0}\bj-\delta^2p|_{y+\delta}\bj
              \approx-\delta^3\pd{p}{y}\bj=-V\pd{p}{y}\bj.
            </me>
            Similarly,
            the force on <m>z=z_0</m> is <m>\delta^2p|_{z_0}\bk</m> and that on <m>z=z_0+\delta</m>
            is <m>-\delta^2p|_{z+\delta}\bk</m>. This gives a contribution
            <me>\delta^2p|_{z_0}\bk-\delta^2p|_{z+\delta}\bk
              \approx-\delta^3\pd{p}{z}\bk=-V\pd{p}{z}\bk.
            </me>
            Hence the total force on the fluid in the cube due to the pressure
            of the surrounding fluid is given by
            <me>-V\pd{p}{x}\bi-V\pd{p}{y}\bj-V\pd{p}{z}\bk=-V\nabla p.</me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Check that you get the same result using the stress tensor of an inviscid fluid
            <xref ref="eq-inviscidstress"/>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The unit normal to the face <m>x=x_0</m> is <m>\hat{\bn}=-\bi</m>,
            and hence the stress at a point in this face is
            <me>\tau=\bsigma\hat{\bn}=-p\bI(-\bi)=p\bi.</me>
            Hence the force on this face equals <m>\delta^2p_{x=x_0}\bi</m>.
            Similarly, the unit normal to the face <m>x=x_0+\delta</m> is <m>\hat{\bn}=\bi</m>,
            and hence the stress at a point in this face is
            <me>\tau=\bsigma\hat{\bn}=-p\bI(\bi)=-p\bi.</me>
            Hence the force on this face equals <m>-\delta^2p_{x=x_0+\delta}\bi</m>.
            Thus the contribution to the force from these two faces is
            <me>\delta^2p|_{x_0}\bi-\delta^2p|_{x+\delta}\bi
              \approx-\delta^3\pd{p}{x}\bi=-V\pd{p}{x}\bi.
            </me>
            The contributions from the other faces can be calculated similarly,
            and the total force on the fluid in the cube due to the pressure
            of the surrounding fluid is given by
            <me>-V\pd{p}{x}\bi-V\pd{p}{y}\bj-V\pd{p}{z}\bk=-V\nabla p.</me>                
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-channel-flow">
      <title>Analysis of flow in a channel</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          A viscous incompressible fluid flows steadily between two stationary rigid boundaries
          at <m>y=\pm h</m>
          under a constant pressure gradient <m>P=-\de p/\de x</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write down the boundary conditions to apply at each of the plates.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The no-slip boundary conditions give
            <me>
              \bu(x,-h,z)=0,\quad \bu(x,h,z)=0
            </me>
            for all <m>x</m> and <m>z</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The velocity is steady and therefore independent of <m>t</m>.
            Explain why it is also reasonable to assume that the velocity profile
            is independent of <m>x</m> and <m>z</m>,
            and also that the <m>z</m>-component of the velocity is zero <m>w=0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since the plates are infinite in the <m>x</m> and <m>z</m> directions,
            and the pressure gradient is constant,
            there is no preferred location in these directions,
            and hence the velocity profile is independent of <m>x</m> and <m>z</m>.
            Furthermore, since there is no pressure gradient in the <m>z</m> direction,
            there is no driving force for flow in this direction,
            and hence the <m>z</m>-component of the velocity is zero (<m>w=0</m>).
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the continuity equation to show that the <m>y</m>-component of the velocity
            is also zero (<m>v=0</m>).
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The continuity equation for an incompressible fluid is
            <me>
              \pd{u}{x}+\pd{v}{y}+\pd{w}{z}=0.
            </me>
            Since the velocity is independent of <m>x</m> and <m>z</m>,
            the first and third terms are zero, and hence
            <me>
              \pd{v}{y}=0.
            </me>
            Since the plates are rigid boundaries, there is no flow through them,
            and hence the no-penetration boundary conditions give
            <me>
              v(x,-h,z)=0,\quad v(x,h,z)=0
            </me>
            for all <m>x</m> and <m>z</m>.
            Since <m>v</m> is independent of <m>y</m> and zero at both <m>y=-h</m> and <m>y=h</m>,
            it follows that <m>v=0</m> for all <m>y</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Hence the only non-zero component of the velocity is the <m>x</m>-component, <m>u</m>,
            and this only depends on <m>y</m>, <m>u(y)</m>. Check that the profile
            <me>
              u=\frac{P}{2\mu}\left(h^2-y^2\right)
            </me>
            satisfies the boundary conditions.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            At <m>y=-h</m>, we have
            <me>
              u(-h)=\frac{P}{2\mu}\left(h^2-(-h)^2\right)
              =\frac{P}{2\mu}(h^2-h^2)=0,
            </me>
            and at <m>y=h</m>, we have
            <me>
              u(h)=\frac{P}{2\mu}\left(h^2-h^2\right)
              =\frac{P}{2\mu}(h^2-h^2)=0.
            </me>
            Hence the profile satisfies the boundary conditions.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The velocity profile increases as <m>P</m> increases and decreases as <m>\mu</m> increases.
            Explain why this is to be expected. Thus, although you cannot yet prove this is the correct
            velocity profile (you will soon be able to do so), this profile does look reasonable from
            what you already know.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            A larger pressure gradient <m>P</m> means a larger driving force for the flow,
            and hence a larger velocity.
            A larger viscosity <m>\mu</m> means a larger resistance to the flow,
            and hence a smaller velocity.
            Therefore, it is to be expected that the velocity profile increases as <m>P</m> increases
            and decreases as <m>\mu</m> increases.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the three components of the stress vector,
            the force per unit area that the fluid exerts,
            on each of the two plates.
            You may assume that the pressure equals <m>p_0</m> at <m>x=0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The pressure at a general point is given by
            <me>
              p=p_0-Px.
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            At <m>y=-h</m>, the normal stress is given by the pressure, pointing into the plate:
            <me>
              \tau_y=-p=-p_0+Px.
            </me>
            (note the negative sign as "into the plate" is in the <m>-y</m>-direction).
            The <m>x</m>-component of the shear stress at <m>y=-h</m> is given by
            <me>
              \tau_x=\mu\pd{u}{y}=\mu\pd{}{y}\left[\frac{P}{2\mu}(h^2-y^2)\right]
              =\mu\left(-\frac{P}{\mu}y\right)=Ph
            </me>
            (note that this is positive since the fluid is pushing the plate in the positive <m>x</m>-direction).
            The <m>z</m>-component of the shear stress at <m>y=-h</m> is zero since <m>w=0</m>.
            Hence
            <me>
              \tau=(Ph,-p_0+Px,0).
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            At <m>y=h</m>, the normal stress is given by the pressure, pointing into the plate:
            <me>
              \tau_y=p_0-Px
            </me>
            (note the sign change compared to the previous part as "into the plate" is in the <m>+y</m>-direction).
            The <m>x</m>-component of the shear stress at <m>y=h</m> is given by
            <me>
              \tau_x=-\mu\pd{u}{y}=-\mu\pd{}{y}\left[\frac{P}{2\mu}(h^2-y^2)\right]
              =-\mu\left(-\frac{P}{\mu}y\right)=Ph.
            </me>
            Note that the formula used has a negative sign as "into the fluid" is in the <m>-y</m>-direction.
            The overall sign is positive since the fluid is pushing the plate in the positive <m>x</m>-direction.
            (It is good to check signs after this kind of calculation by checking the direction of the force.)
            The <m>z</m>-component of the shear stress at <m>y=h</m> is zero since <m>w=0</m>.
            Hence
            <me>
              \tau=(Ph,p_0-Px,0).
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compare the stresses on the two plates. Why is this to be expected?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The normal stresses on the two plates are equal in magnitude but opposite in direction,
            as expected since the pressure acts equally on both plates,
            but "into the plates" is a different direction.
          </p>
          <p>
            The shear stresses on the two plates are equal in magnitude and direction,
            indicating that the fluid is exerting the same tangential force on both plates
            in the direction of the flow.
            This is also expected since the plane <m>y=0</m> is a plane of symmetry.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Force on a blob of fluid</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          <em>Based on Exercises 6.1 and 6.2 in <xref ref="ref-acheson"/>.</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          In this exercise, you will find an expression for force per unit volume acting
          on an incompressible Newtonian fluid.
          You will do this by finding the force acting on a small blob of the fluid
          as an integral over its volume. First you will find a new expression
          for the stress vector at the blob's surface,
          which makes the rest of the calculation easier.
          with normal <m>\hat{\bn}</m>,
          and use this to find an expression for the force on a blob of fluid.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Recall that <m>\btau=\bsigma\cdot\hat{\bn}</m> is the stress vector
            acting on a surface with normal <m>\hat{\bn}</m>, and this is given by
            <me>
              \tau_i=-pn_i+\mu\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\left(\pd{u_i}{x_j}+\pd{u_j}{x_i}\right).
            </me>
            Show that this is identical to
            <me>
              \btau=-p\hat{\bn}+\mu\left[2(\hat{\bn}\cdot\nabla)\bu
              +\hat{\bn}\times(\nabla\times\bu)\right].
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            You may use the fact that 
            <me>
              \hat{\bn}\times\left(\nabla\times\bu\right)
              =\nabla(\hat{\bn}\cdot\bu)-(\hat{\bn}\cdot\nabla)\bu,
            </me>
            where, in the first bracket,
            the operator <m>\nabla</m> acts on <m>\bu</m> but not <m>\bn</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The <m>i</m>th component of
            <me>
              \hat{\bn}\times\left(\nabla\times\bu\right)
              =\nabla(\hat{\bn}\cdot\bu)-(\hat{\bn}\cdot\nabla)\bu,
            </me>
            is
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \left[\hat{\bn}\times(\nabla\times\bu)\right]_i
                &amp;=\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\pd{u_j}{x_i}-(\hat{\bn}\cdot\nabla)u_i
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;=\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\pd{u_j}{x_i}-\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\pd{u_i}{x_j}.
              </mrow>
            </md>
            Hence, the <m>i</m>th component of the target expression is
            <md>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\left\{-p\bn+\mu\left[2(\hat{\bn}\cdot\nabla)\bu
                +\hat{\bn}\times(\nabla\times\bu)\right]\right\}_i
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;=-pn_i+\mu\left[2\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\pd{u_i}{x_j}
                +\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\pd{u_j}{x_i}-\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\pd{u_i}{x_j}\right]
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;=-pn_i+\mu\left[\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\pd{u_i}{x_j}
                +\sum_{j=1}^3n_j\pd{u_j}{x_i}\right]
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;=\sum_{j=1}^3\left[-p\delta_{ij}+\mu\left(\pd{u_i}{x_j}
                +\pd{u_j}{x_i}\right)\right]n_j
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;=\sum_{j=1}^3\sigma_{ij}n_j
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;=\btau_i,
              </mrow>
            </md>
            as required.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Hence show that the force on a blob of incompressible fluid of volume <m>V</m> due to the
            surrounding fluid is given by
            <me>
              \bF=\iint_S\btau\de S
              =\iiint_V\left(-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu\right)\de V,
            </me>
            where <m>S</m> is the surface of the blob of fluid.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Use the following vector calculus identities:
            <md>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\iint_S\phi\bn\de S=\iiint_V-\nabla\phi\de V,
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\iint_S\bF\times\hat{\bn}\de S=-\iiint_V\nabla\times\bF\de V,
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\iint_S(\hat{\bn}\cdot\nabla)\phi\de S=\iiint_V\nabla^2\phi\de V,
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\nabla^2\bF=\nabla(\nabla\cdot\bF)-\nabla\times(\nabla\times\bF).
              </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </hint>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We have
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \bf=&amp;\iint_S\btau\de S
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\iint_S\left\{-p\hat{\bn}+\mu\left[2(\hat{\bn}\cdot\nabla)\bu
                +\hat{\bn}\times(\nabla\times\bu)\right]\right\}\de S.
              </mrow>
            </md>
            We now make use of the vector calculus identities given in the hint.
            The first term becoems
            <me>
              \iint_S-p\hat{\bn}\de S=\iiint_V-\nabla p\de V,
            </me>
            the second term becomes
            <me>
              \iint_S2\mu(\hat{\bn}\cdot\nabla)\bu\de S
              =\iiint_V2\mu\nabla^2\bu\de V,
            </me>
            and for the third term,
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \iint_S\mu\hat{\bn}\times(\nabla\times\bu)\de S
                =&amp;-\iint_S\mu(\nabla\times\bu)\times\hat{\bn}\de S
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\iiint_V\mu\nabla\times(\nabla\times\bu)\de V,
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\iiint_V\mu\nabla(\nabla\cdot\bu)-\mu\nabla^2\bu\de V.
              </mrow>
            </md>
            Hence, since the fluid is incompressible and <m>\nabla\cdot\bu=0</m>,
            the third term becomes
            <me>
              \\\int_V-\mu\nabla^2\bu\de V.
            </me>
            Combining these three results gives
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \bF=&amp;\iiint_V\left(-\nabla p+2\mu\nabla^2\bu-\mu\nabla^2\bu\right)\de V
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\iiint_V\left(-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu\right)\de V,
              </mrow>
            </md>
            as required.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Deduce that, if the blob is small, the net force on it per unit volume of fluid
            equals <m>-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            If the blob is small, then the integrand in the expression for the force
            varies little over the volume of the blob, and so
            <me>
              \bF\approx\left(-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu\right)V,
            </me>
            where <m>V</m> is the volume of the blob. Hence the force per unit volume
            is given by
            <me>
              \frac{\bF}{V}=-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu,
            </me>
            as required.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-general-deformation-fluid-element">
      <title>General deformation of a fluid element</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          <em>Based on Exercise 6.7 in <xref ref="ref-acheson"/>.</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          In this exercise, you will consider the general deformation of a fluid element
          in an incompressible Newtonian fluid.
          You will show that the deformation can be expressed as a combination of
          three types of motion: translation, rotation and pure strain.
        </p>
        <p>
          Note that, if the fluid were also compressible,
          there would be a fourth type of motion,
          namely expansion or contraction.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>P</m> be a point in the fluid with position vector <m>\bx</m>,
            and let <m>Q</m> be a nearby point with position vector <m>\bx+\bs</m>.
            Explain why the velocity at point <m>Q</m> can be expressed in terms
            of that at point <m>P</m> as
            <me>
              \bu_Q=\bu_P+(\bs\cdot\nabla)\bu.
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The velocity at point <m>Q</m> can be expressed as a Taylor series expansion
            about point <m>P</m>:
            <me>
              \bu_Q=\bu_P+\left(\bs\cdot\nabla\right)\bu
              +\frac{1}{2!}\left(\bs\cdot\nabla\right)^2\bu
              +\frac{1}{3!}\left(\bs\cdot\nabla\right)^3\bu+\cdots.
            </me>
            Since <m>Q</m> is a nearby point to <m>P</m>, the higher order terms
            in <m>\bs</m> are negligible, and hence we have
            <me>
              \bu_Q=\bu_P+(\bs\cdot\nabla)\bu,
            </me>
            as required.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Show that
            <men xml:id="eq-pq">
              \bu_Q=\bu_P+\frac12(\nabla_x\times\bu)\times\bs
              +\frac12\nabla_s(\sum_{i=1}^3\sum_{j=1}^3e_{ij}s_is_j),
            </men>
            where <m>\nabla_x</m> denotes differentiation with respect to the
            components of <m>\bx</m>, <m>\nabla_s</m> denotes differentiation with respect to the
            components of <m>\bs</m>, and
            <me>
              e_{ij}=\frac12\left(\pd{u_i}{x_j}+\pd{u_j}{x_i}\right)
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            You may use the fact that
            <m>(\nabla\times\bf)\times\bg=\bg\cdot\nabla\bf-\nabla(\bg\cdot\bf)</m>,
            where, in the second term on the right-hand side,
            the operator <m>\nabla</m> acts on <m>\bf</m> but not <m>\bg</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We have that the <m>k</m>th component of the final term of the target expression is
            <md>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\left\{\frac12\nabla_s(\sum_{i=1}^3\sum_{j=1}^3e_{ij}s_is_j)\right\}_k
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac12\pd{}{s_k}(\sum_{i=1}^3\sum_{j=1}^3e_{ij}s_is_j)
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac12(\sum_{i=1}^3e_{ik}s_i+\sum_{j=1}^3e_{kj}s_j)
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac12\sum_{i=1}^3(e_{ik}s_i+e_{ki}s_i)
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\sum_{i=1}^3e_{ik}s_i,
              </mrow>
            </md>
            where the final equality uses the fact that
            the rate-of-strain tensor is symmetric <m>e_{ij}=e_{ji}</m>.
            Substituting for <m>e_{ik}</m> gives
            <md>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\sum_{i=1}^3e_{ik}s_i
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac12\sum_{i=1}^3\left(\pd{u_i}{x_k}+\pd{u_k}{x_i}\right)s_i.
              </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            Using the given vector identity, the <m>k</m>th component of the second term
            of the target expression is
            <md>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\left\{\frac12(\nabla_x\times\bu)\times\bs\right\}_k
              </mrow>
              <mrow>  
                =&amp;\frac12\left\{\bs\cdot\nabla_x\bu-\nabla_x(\bs\cdot\bu)\right\}_k
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac12\left\{\sum_{i=1}^3s_i\pd{u_k}{x_i}
                -\sum_{i=1}^3s_i\pd{u_i}{x_k}\right\}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>  
                =&amp;\frac12\sum_{i=1}^3\left(\pd{u_k}{x_i}-\pd{u_i}{x_k}\right)s_i.
              </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            Hence the <m>k</m>th component of the sum of the second and the third terms of the target expression is
            <md>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\frac12(\nabla_x\times\bu)\times\bs
                +\frac12\nabla_s(\sum_{i=1}^3\sum_{j=1}^3e_{ij}s_is_j)
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac12\sum_{i=1}^3\left(\pd{u_k}{x_i}-\pd{u_i}{x_k}\right)s_i
                +\frac12\sum_{i=1}^3\left(\pd{u_i}{x_k}+\pd{u_k}{x_i}\right)s_i
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\sum_{i=1}^3\pd{u_k}{x_i}s_i,
              </mrow>
            </md>
            which is the <m>k</m>th component of <m>(\bs\cdot\nabla)\bu</m>, thus proving the result.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain why the three terms on the right-hand side of the expression
            in the previous part represent translation, rotation and pure strain,
            respectively.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The first term <m>\bu_P</m> represents translation since it is the velocity
                  at point <m>P</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The second term
                  <m>\frac12(\nabla_x\times\bu)\times\bs</m>
                  represents rotation since, setting <m>\bOmega=\nabla_x\times\bu/2=\bomega/2</m>,
                  this term is of the form <m>\bOmega\times\bs</m>,
                  which is purely rotational motion about point <m>P</m> (see <xref ref="ex-rotating-flow"/>).
                  Note also that this again shows a result that we used in <xref ref="sec-vorticity"/>
                  that the vorticity <m>\bomega</m> is twice the angular velocity
                  since <m>\bOmega=\bomega/2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The third term
                  <m>\frac12\nabla_s(\sum_{i=1}^3\sum_{j=1}^3e_{ij}s_is_j)</m>
                  represents pure strain since it depends on the rate-of-strain tensor <m>e_{ij}</m>,
                  which describes how the fluid element is deformed without rotation.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-velocity-decomposition">
      <title>Decomposition of a shear flow</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          <em>Based on Exercise 6.8 in <xref ref="ref-acheson"/>.</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          In this problem, you will apply the equation from the previous problem
          <xref ref="ex-general-deformation-fluid-element"/>
          to a shear flow <m>\bu=(\beta y,0,0)</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use <xref ref="eq-pq"/> to decompose <m>\bu</m> into its local (i) translational,
            (ii) rotational, and (iii) pure straining components.
            For (iii), find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors,
            which give the principle directions of strain.
            Sketch each of the components (ii) and (iii).
          </p>
          <p>
            Note that this example is a special case in which the rotational
            and pure straining components are uniform over the fluid domain.
            More generally, both will vary.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            (ii) The vorticity
            <me>
              \bomega=(0,0,-\beta),
            </me>
            and therefore the rotational component is
            <me>
              \frac12\bomega\times\bs
              =\frac12\beta(s_y,-s_x,0),
            </me>
            which is clockwise rotation with angular velocity <m>\beta/2</m>,
            see left sketch in <xref ref="fig-shear-flow-decomposition"/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            (iii) We have the rate-of-strain tensor
            <me>
              \be=\left(\begin{matrix}
              0&amp;\beta/2&amp;0\\
              \beta/2&amp;0&amp;0\\
              0&amp;0&amp;0
              \end{matrix}\right).
            </me>
            Hence
            <me>
              \frac12\nabla_s\left(\sum_{j=1}^3\sum_{i=1}^3e_{ij}s_is_j\right)
              =\frac{\beta}2\nabla_s\left(s_1s_2\right)
              =\frac{\beta}2\left(s_y,s_x,0\right)
            </me>
            (note that we are interchanging between <m>s=(s_1,s_2,s_3)</m>
            and <m>(s_x,s_y,s_z)</m>).
            The eigenvalues <m>\lambda</m> of <m>\be</m> satisfy
            <me>
              -\lambda^3+\frac14\beta^2\lambda=0,
            </me>
            which has solutions <m>\lambda=0,\pm\beta/2</m>.
            The associated eigenvectors are
            <me>
              \hat{\mathbf{k}},
              \quad\left(\frac1{\sqrt{2}},\frac1{\sqrt{2}},0\right),
              \quad\left(-\frac1{\sqrt{2}},\frac1{\sqrt{2}},0\right).
            </me>
            This corresponds to expansion along the line <m>x=y</m>
            and contraction along <m>x=-y</m>, see middle sketch in
            <xref ref="fig-shear-flow-decomposition"/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The solution is illustrated in <xref ref="fig-shear-flow-decomposition"/>.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="fig-shear-flow-decomposition">
            <caption>Sketches showing the decomposition of the flow into
