    <exercise xml:id="ps-Cauchy-equation">
      <title>Derivation of the Cauchy equation</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          In this problem, you will derive the Cauchy equation
          <xref ref="eqn-cauchy-equation"/> for the conservation of linear momentum
          in an incompressible fluid that is not necessarily Newtonian
          (the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equation only applies to Newtonian fluids).
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider a volume <m>V(t)</m> moving with the fluid that,
            at the time <m>t</m> is the small cube of fluid as shown in
            <xref ref="fig-small-cube"/>, and apply the Reynolds Transport Theorem
            <xref ref="eqn-RTT"/> to the fluid in this volume.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We consider a volume <m>V</m> with surface <m>S</m>
            consisting of a small cube of side length <m>\delta</m>,
            as shown in <xref ref="fig-small-cube"/>. We apply the
            Reynolds Transport Theorem to the fluid in the cube:
            <me>
              \dd{}{t} \iiint_{V(t)} f \, \de{x} \, \de{y} \, \de{z} = \iiint_{V(t)} \left[
              \pd{f}{t} + \nabla \cdot (f\bu)\right] \, \de{x} \, \de{y} \, \de{z},
            </me>
            where <m>f</m> is any function, a vector or a scalar.
          </p>
          <p>
            Setting <m>\bf=\rho\bu</m> equal to the momentum per unit volume in the fluid,
            the integral equals the momentum of the fluid in the cube,
            and the time derivative is the rate of change of momentum,
            which is the total force acting on the fluid in the cube.
          </p>
          <p>
            The total force equals the sum of the surface forces and body forces.
            The body force equals the force of gravity: <m>\rho V\bg</m>.
            The surface forces are an integral:
            <me>
              \iint_S\btau\,\de S=\iint_S\bsigma\bn\,\de S;
            </me>
            and we sum the contributions over the six faces in pairs:
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Front and back faces: The contribution on the back face (<m>\bn=-\bi</m>) is
                  <me>
                    -\delta^2\left.\left(\begin{array}{c}
                    \sigma_{11}\\\sigma_{12}\\\sigma_{13}
                    \end{array}\right)\right|_{x=x_0}
                  </me>
                  and on the front face (<m>\bn=\bi</m>), it is
                  <me>
                    \delta^2\left.\left(\begin{array}{c}
                    \sigma_{11}\\\sigma_{12}\\\sigma_{13}
                    \end{array}\right)\right|_{x=x_0+\delta}.
                  </me>
                  The sum of these is
                  <me>
                    \delta^2\left.\left(\begin{array}{c}
                    \sigma_{11}\\\sigma_{12}\\\sigma_{13}
                    \end{array}\right)\right|_{x=x_0+\delta}
                    -\delta^2\left.\left(\begin{array}{c}
                    \sigma_{11}\\\sigma_{12}\\\sigma_{13}
                    \end{array}\right)\right|_{x=x_0}
                    =\delta^3\pd{}{x}\left(\begin{array}{c}
                    \sigma_{11}\\\sigma_{12}\\\sigma_{13}
                    \end{array}\right).
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Left and right faces: In a similar way, the contribution is
                  <me>
                    \delta^3\pd{}{y}\left(\begin{array}{c}
                    \sigma_{21}\\\sigma_{22}\\\sigma_{23}
                    \end{array}\right).
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Bottom and top faces: The contribution is
                  <me>
                    \delta^3\pd{}{z}\left(\begin{array}{c}
                    \sigma_{31}\\\sigma_{32}\\\sigma_{33}
                    \end{array}\right).
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
            Hence, the surface force is given by
            <me>
              \delta^3\pd{}{x}\left(\begin{array}{c}
              \sigma_{11}\\\sigma_{12}\\\sigma_{13}
              \end{array}\right)
              +\delta^3\pd{}{y}\left(\begin{array}{c}
              \sigma_{21}\\\sigma_{22}\\\sigma_{23}
              \end{array}\right)
              +\delta^3\pd{}{z}\left(\begin{array}{c}
              \sigma_{31}\\\sigma_{32}\\\sigma_{33}
              \end{array}\right)
              =\delta^3\nabla\cdot\bsigma,
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            Hence
            <me>
              \rho V\bg+\delta^3\nabla\cdot\bsigma
              =\iiint_{V(t)} \left[\pd{(\rho\bu)}{t} + \nabla \cdot (\rho\bu\bu)\right]\,\de{x}\,\de{y}\,\de{z},
            </me>
            Since the cube is small,
            the right-hand side is approximately the volume <m>V</m> times
            the integrand evaluated at a point in <m>V</m>.
            Dividing by <m>V=\delta^3</m> gives
            <me>
              \rho\bg+\nabla\cdot\bsigma
              =\pd{(\rho\bu)}{t} + \nabla \cdot ((\rho\bu)\bu).
            </me>
            Since <m>\rho</m> is constant,
            <me>
              \rho\bg+\nabla\cdot\bsigma
              =\rho\pd{\bu}{t} + \rho\bu\cdot\nabla\bu+\rho(\nabla\cdot\bu)\bu.
            </me>
            Since the fluid is incompressible, we have <m>\nabla\cdot\bu=0</m>, and,
            rearranging, we obtain the Cauchy equation:
            <me>
              \rho\left(\pd{\bu}{t} + \bu\cdot\nabla\bu\right)
              =\nabla\cdot\bsigma+\rho\bg
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-limits-low-high-Reynolds">
      <title>Limits of low and high Reynolds number</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          An incompressible Newtonian fluid with density <m>\rho</m> and
          shear viscosity <m>\mu</m> flows in a space with
          a typical lengthscale <m>L</m> and velocity scale <m>U</m>.          
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Perform a nondimensionalisation of
            the Navier<ndash/>Stokes <xref ref="eqn-navierstokes"/> and
            continuity <xref ref="eqn-incompressibledef"/> equations, using a scale <m>P</m>
            for the pressure and <m>T</m> for time, and writing the gravitational acceleration
            as <m>\bg=g\hat{\bg}</m>, where <m>\hat{\bg}</m> is a unit vector in the direction of <m>\bg</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We have
            <me>
              \rho\pd{\bu}{t}+\rho\bu\cdot\nabla\bu=-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu+\rho{\bg},\quad
              \nabla\cdot\bu=0,
            </me>
            which, after nondimensionalising, become
            <me>
              \frac{\rho U}{T}\pd{\bu^*}{t^*}+\frac{\rho U^2}{L}\bu^*\cdot\nabla^*\bu^*
              =-\frac{P}{L}\nabla^* p^*+\frac{\mu U}{L^2}\nabla^{*2}\bu^*+\rho g\hat{\bg},\quad
              \frac{U}{L}\nabla^*\cdot\bu^*=0.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Choose a suitable timescale <m>T</m> so that the inertial terms balance and
            multiply the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equation by a suitable factor so that
            the nondimensional viscous term has coefficient 1. What do you notice
            about the coefficient of the inertial terms?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We set the coefficients of the two inertial terms equal:
            <me>
              \frac{\rho U}{T}=\frac{\rho U^2}{L}
              \quad\Rightarrow\quad
              T=\frac{L}{U}.
            </me>
            Multiplying the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equation by <m>L^2/(\mu U)</m>, we get
            <me>
              \mathrm{Re}\DD{\bu^*}{t^*}
              =-\frac{LP}{\mu U}\nabla^* p^*+\nabla^{*2}\bu^*+\frac{\rho L^2g}{\mu U}\hat{\bg}.
            </me>
            The coefficient multiplying the inertial terms is the Reynolds number <m>\mathrm{Re}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Hence, in the case of a low-Reynolds-number flow, <m>\mathrm{Re}\ll1</m>,
            show that, to leading order,
            the equations simplify to one of the following three cases:
            <me>
              0=-\nabla p+\rho{\bg},
            </me>
            or
            <me>
              0=-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu+\rho{\bg},\quad
              \nabla\cdot\bu=0,
            </me>
            or
            <me>
              0=-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu,\quad
              \nabla\cdot\bu=0.
            </me>
            Specify the conditions under which each of these equations is obtained.
            In the latter two cases, we term the equations governing the fluid velocity
            <em>the Stokes equations</em>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            In this case, the inertial terms are small compared to the viscous terms,
            so we can neglect them.
            The gravitational acceleration term has order of magnitude <m>\rho L^2g/(\mu U)</m>.
            We need to consider the cases in which this is large, order one or small:
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>\rho L^2g/(\mu U)\gg1</m>, the pressre have a predominantly hydrostatic
                  pressure profile, with the fluid dynamical problem being a small perturbation
                  to the background static problem.
                  Thus the pressure gradient balances this term:
                  <me>
                    \frac{LP}{\mu U}=\frac{\rho L^2g}{\mu U}
                    \quad\Rightarrow\quad
                    P=\rho Lg,
                  </me>
                  and, to leading order, the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equation becomes
                  <me>
                    0=-\nabla^* p^*+\hat{\bg}.
                  </me>
                  Once we have solved this problem, we could in principle solve a
                  secondary problem to find the fluid flow. Thus the dimensional problem is
                  <me>
                    0=-\nabla p+\rho\bg.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>\rho L^2g/(\mu U)</m> is of order 1, the gravitational acceleration
                  term balances the leading-order terms in the equation, and we set
                  <me>
                    \frac{LP}{\mu U}=1\quad\Rightarrow\quad P=\frac{\mu U}{L}.
                  </me>
                  We obtain the leading-order system
                  <me>
                    0=-\nabla^* p^*+\nabla^{*2}\bu^*+\frac{\rho L^2g}{\mu U}\hat{\bg},
                  </me>
                  and redimensionalising, we get
                  <me>
                    0=-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu,
                  </me>
                  and the continuity equation is retained in full:
                  <me>
                    \nabla\cdot\bu=0.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>\rho L^2g/(\mu U)\ll1</m>, the gravitational acceleration
                  term is small compared to the leading-order terms in the equation, and we set
                  <me>
                    \frac{LP}{\mu U}=1\quad\Rightarrow\quad P=\frac{\mu U}{L}.
                  </me>
                  We obtain the leading-order system
                  <me>
                    0=-\nabla^* p^*+\nabla^{*2}\bu^*,
                  </me>
                  and redimensionalising, we get
                  <me>
                    0=-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu,
                  </me>
                  and the continuity equation is retained in full:
                  <me>
                    \nabla\cdot\bu=0.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In the case of a high-Reynolds-number flow, <m>\mathrm{Re}\gg1</m>,
            show that, to leading order,
            the equations simplify to one of the following three cases:
            <me>
              0=-\nabla p+\rho{\bg},
            </me>
            or
            <me>
              \rho\DD{u}{t}=-\nabla p+\rho{\bg},\quad
              \nabla\cdot\bu=0,
            </me>
            or
            <me>
              \rho\DD{u}{t}=-\nabla p,\quad
              \nabla\cdot\bu=0.
            </me>
            Specify the conditions under which each of these equations is obtained.
            In the latter two cases, we term the equations governing the fluid velocity
            <em>the Euler equations</em>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            In this case, the viscous terms are small compared to the inertial terms,
            so we can neglect them.
            Dividing the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equation by <m>\mathrm{Re}</m>,
            <me>
              \DD{\bu^*}{t^*}
              =-\frac{P}{\rho U^2}\nabla^* p^*+\frac{Lg}{U^2}\hat{\bg}.
            </me>
            The gravitational acceleration term now has order of magnitude <m>Lg/U^2</m>.
            We need to consider the cases in which this is large, order one or small:
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>Lg/U^2\gg1</m>, the pressre have a predominantly hydrostatic
                  pressure profile, with the fluid dynamical problem being a small perturbation
                  to the background static problem.
                  Thus the pressure gradient balances this term:
                  <me>
                    \frac{P}{\rho U^2}=\frac{Lg}{U^2}
                    \quad\Rightarrow\quad
                    P=\rho Lg,
                  </me>
                  and, to leading order, the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equation becomes
                  <me>
                    0=-\nabla^* p^*+\hat{\bg}.
                  </me>
                  As in the low-Reynolds-number cases,
                  once we have solved this problem, we could in principle solve a
                  secondary problem to find the fluid flow. Thus the dimensional problem is
                  <me>
                    0=-\nabla p+\rho\bg.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>Lg/U^2</m> is of order 1, the gravitational acceleration
                  term balances the leading-order terms in the equation, and we set
                  <me>
                    \frac{P}{\rho U^2}=1\quad\Rightarrow\quad P=\rho U^2.
                  </me>
                  We obtain the leading-order system
                  <me>
                    \DD{u^*}{t^*}=-\nabla^* p^*+\frac{Lg}{U^2}\hat{\bg},
                  </me>
                  and redimensionalising, we get
                  <me>
                    \rho\DD{u}{t}=-\nabla p+\rho\bg,
                  </me>
                  and the continuity equation is retained in full:
                  <me>
                    \nabla\cdot\bu=0.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>Lg/U^2\ll1</m>, the gravitational acceleration
                  term is small compared to the leading-order terms in the equation, and we set
                  <me>
                    \frac{P}{\rho U^2}=1\quad\Rightarrow\quad P=\rho U^2.
                  </me>
                  We obtain the leading-order system
                  <me>
                    \DD{u^*}{t^*}=-\nabla^* p^*,
                  </me>
                  and redimensionalising, we get
                  <me>
                    \rho\DD{u}{t}=-\nabla p,
                  </me>
                  and the continuity equation is retained in full:
                  <me>
                    \nabla\cdot\bu=0.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-hagen-poiseuille-flow">
      <title>Hagen<ndash/>Poiseuille flow</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          In this exercise you will review the derivation of Poiseuille flow and prove the
          Hagen<ndash/>Poiseuille formula <xref ref="hagen-poiseuille-formula"/>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Review the derivation <xref ref="sec-poiseuille"/>, making your own notes.
            Use the flow profile to prove the formula <xref ref="hagen-poiseuille-formula"/>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We have that the volumetric flux along the pipe equals
            (<m>A</m> is a circular cross-section <m>z=\mathrm{constant}</m> of the pipe)
            <md>
              <mrow>
                Q=&amp;\iint_Aw\,\de A
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^a\frac{G}{4\mu}\left(a^2-r^2\right)r\,\de r\,\de \theta
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;2\pi\frac{G}{4\mu}\int_0^a\left(a^2r-r^3\right)\,\de r
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac{\pi G}{2\mu}\left[\frac{a^2r^2}{2}-\frac{r^4}{4}\right]_0^a
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac{\pi G}{2\mu}\left(\frac{a^4}{2}-\frac{a^4}{4}\right)
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;\frac{\pi Ga^4}{8\mu},
              </mrow>
            </md>
            where <m>G=\Delta p/L</m> is the pressure gradient. Rearranging,
            <me>
              \Delta p=\frac{8\mu LQ}{\pi a^4},
            </me>
            as expected.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <title>Flow outside a cylinder</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          A Newtonian incompressible fluid of density <m>\rho</m> and
          shear viscosity <m>\mu</m> surrounds a circular cylinder of radius <m>a</m>.
          Working in cylindrical polar coordinates, the cylinder surface is at <m>r=a</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Navier<ndash/>Stokes and continuity equations in cylindrical polar coordinates
          read:
          <md>
            <mrow>
              &amp;\rho\left(\pd{u_r}{t}+u_r\pd{u_r}{r}+\frac{u_{\theta}}{r}\pd{u_r}{\theta}+u_z\pd{u_r}{z}-\frac{u_{\theta}^2}{r}\right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              =&amp;-\pd{p}{r}
              +\mu\left(\nabla^2u_r-\frac{u_r}{r^2}-\frac{2}{r^2}\pd{u_\theta}{\theta}\right),
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              &amp;\rho\left(\pd{u_{\theta}}{t}+u_r\pd{u_{\theta}}{r}+\frac{u_{\theta}}{r}\pd{u_{\theta}}{\theta}+u_z\pd{u_{\theta}}{z}+\frac{u_ru_{\theta}}{r}\right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              =&amp;-\frac{1}{r}\pd{p}{\theta}
              +\mu\left(\nabla^2u_\theta+\frac{2}{r^2}\pd{u_r}{\theta}-\frac{u_{\theta}}{r^2}\right),
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              &amp;\rho\left(\pd{u_z}{t}+u_r\pd{u_z}{r}+\frac{u_{\theta}}{r}\pd{u_z}{\theta}+u_z\pd{u_z}{z}\right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              =&amp;-\pd{p}{z}
              +\mu\nabla^2u_z,
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              &amp;\frac1r\pd{}{r}\left(ru_r\right)+\frac1r\pd{u_\theta}{\theta}+\pd{u_z}{z}=0,
            </mrow>
          </md>
          where the Laplacian is defined by its action on a function <m>A(r,\theta,z)</m>:
          <me>
            \nabla^2A=\frac1r\pd{}{r}\left(r\pd{A}{r}\right)+\frac1{r^2}\pd{^2A}{\theta^2}+\pd{^2A}{z^2},
          </me>
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In the case that the surface of the cylinder is porous and there is a uniform suction
            inside it, which induces a steady flow into the cylinder with inflow velocity
            <m>U</m> at the surface, you may assume that the flow is steady,
            two-dimensional and axisymmetric. With these assumptions,
            use the continuity equation to show that
            <me>
              u_r=-\frac{Ua}{r}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Axisymmetry implies <m>u_\theta=0</m> and two-dimensional flow implies <m>u_z=0</m>.
            With these assumptions, the continuity equation becomes
            <me>
              \frac1r\pd{}{r}\left(ru_r\right)=0.
            </me>
            Multiplying by <m>r</m> and integrating,
            <me>
              ru_r=A\quad\Rightarrow\quad u_r=\frac{A}{r},
            </me>
            where <m>A</m> is constant. The boundary condition on <m>r=a</m> reads
            <m>u_r=-U</m>, and hence
            <me>
              -U=\frac{A}{a}\quad\Rightarrow\quad A=-aU.
            </me>
            Substituting this in,
            <me>
              u_r=\frac{-aU}{r}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Show that the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations reduce to
            <me>
              \pd{p}{r}
              =-\left(\rho aU+2\mu\right)\frac{aU}{r^3}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We substitute the assumptions into the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations,
            which state that all <m>t</m>, <m>\theta</m> and <m>z</m> derivatives are zero
            and <m>u_\theta=u_z=0</m>. The equations become:
            <md>
              <mrow>
                &amp;\rho\left(u_r\pd{u_r}{r}-\frac{u_{\theta}^2}{r}\right)
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                =&amp;-\pd{p}{r}
                +\mu\left(\nabla^2u_r-\frac{u_r}{r^2}\right),
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                0=&amp;0,
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                0=&amp;0,
              </mrow>
            </md>
            and
            <me>
              nabla^2u_r
              =\frac1r\pd{}{r}\left(r\pd{u_r}{r}\right)
              =\pd{^2u_r}{r^2}+\frac1r\pd{u_r}{r}.
            </me>
            Hence, the only non-trivial equation is the <m>r</m>-component, which reduces to
            <me>
              \rho u_r\pd{u_r}{r}
              =-\pd{p}{r}
              +\mu\left(\pd{^2u_r}{r^2}+\frac1r\pd{u_r}{r}-\frac{u_r}{r^2}\right).
            </me>
            Substituting the expression for <m>u_r</m>,
            <me>
              \rho \left(-\frac{aU}{r}\right)\left(\frac{aU}{r^2}\right)
              =-\pd{p}{r}
              +\mu\left(-\frac{2aU}{r^3}+\frac{aU}{r^3}-\frac{aU}{r^3}\right),
            </me>
            which simplifies to
            <me>
              \pd{p}{r}=-\frac{\rho a^2U^2}{r^3}-\frac{2\mu aU}{r^3}
              =-\left(\rho aU+2\mu\right)\frac{aU}{r^3},
            </me>
            as required.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve this to find the pressure field, given that the far-field pressure is <m>p_0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We solve the equation, applying the boundary condition as <m>r\rightarrow\infty</m>
            to find that
            <me>
              \pd{p}{r}=p_0+\left(\rho aU+2\mu\right)\frac{aU}{2r^2},
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>

