            </me>
            (the minus sign occurs since the vector into the fluid points in the <m>-y</m>-direction)
            and the <m>z</m>-component of the stress is zero since the flow is two-dimensional.
            The <m>x</m>-component equals
            <me>
              \tau=-\mu (-Gd)=\mu Gd.
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            For the plate at <m>y=-k</m>,
            the <m>x</m>-component of the stress is
            <me>
              \tau=\mu\pd{u}{y}
            </me>
            (the plus sign occurs since the vector into the fluid points in the <m>+y</m>-direction)
            and the <m>z</m>-component of the stress is zero since the flow is two-dimensional.
            The <m>x</m>-component equals
            <me>
              \tau=\mu (-G(-d))=\mu Gd.
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            Thus the stress at both plates is <m>\mu Gd</m> in the <m>+x</m>-direction,
            and the force on the whole plate is <m>\mu GdA</m> in the <m>+x</m>-direction.
            Hence the tethering force to keep each plate fixed is <m>\mu GdA</m> in the <m>-x</m>-direction.
          </p>
        </solution>-->
      </task>
    </exercise>
